Textual statistics

Constantine Boussalis

1 February 2022

Overview

This tutorial covers a variety of textual statistics that can be performed on a corpus using quanteda. Specifically, we will discuss basic frequency analysis and how to visualize these results to answer various questions. Next, we will cover the keyness of features in a comparative context. Then we will dive into how to estimate the complexity of text via readability and lexical diversity scores. Lastly, we will cover text similarity metrics; specifically focusing on cosine similarity. The tutorial will use the 2017 UN General Assembly speeches as the working corpus.

Text processing and creation of DFM

Let’s process the text of the speeches using the same methods we learned in our previous tutorial. We will not stem, but will replace collocations.

require(quanteda.textstats)
## Loading required package: quanteda.textstats
toks <- tokens(un_corpus,
               include_docvars = TRUE) %>%
  tokens_tolower() %>%
  tokens_remove(stopwords("english"), padding = TRUE) %>%
  tokens_remove('[\\p{P}\\p{S}]', valuetype = 'regex', padding = TRUE)

unsup_col <- textstat_collocations(toks,
                                   method = "lambda",
                                   size = 2,
                                   min_count = 5,
                                   smoothing = 0.5)

unsup_col <- unsup_col[order(-unsup_col$count),] # sort detected collocations by count (descending)
toks <- tokens_compound(toks, pattern = unsup_col[unsup_col$z > 10])
toks <- tokens_remove(tokens(toks), "") # let's also remove the whitespace placeholders

toks <- tokens(toks, 
               remove_numbers = TRUE,
               remove_punct = TRUE,
               remove_symbols = TRUE,
               remove_hyphens = TRUE,
               remove_separators = TRUE,
               remove_url = TRUE,
               include_docvars = TRUE)
## Warning: remove_hyphens argument is not used.

Frequency analysis

We can perform a number of simple frequency analyses to get a sense of the most talked about terms. How about the top 30 from all speeches:

library(ggplot2)

dfm_freq <- textstat_frequency(dfm_un, n = 30)
# sort features by frequency in descending order
dfm_freq$feature <- with(dfm_freq, reorder(feature, -frequency))
# plot feature frequencies
ggplot(dfm_freq, aes(x = feature, y = frequency)) + ggtitle("Feature frequency of all speeches") +
       geom_point() + theme_minimal() + theme(axis.text.x = element_text(angle = 90, hjust = 1))

Instead of all speeches, we can also look at the feature frequency of the Russian speech.

library(ggplot2)

dfm_russia <- dfm_subset(dfm_un, country == "Russia")
dfm_freq <- textstat_frequency(dfm_russia, n = 30)
# sort features by frequency in descending order
dfm_freq$feature <- with(dfm_freq, reorder(feature, -frequency))
# plot feature frequencies
ggplot(dfm_freq, aes(x = feature, y = frequency)) + ggtitle("Feature frequency of Russian speech") +
       geom_point() + theme_minimal() + theme(axis.text.x = element_text(angle = 90, hjust = 1))

We can also generate a comparison cloud which displays highly frequent words in a wordcloud for up to eight documents. Let’s compare the most frequent features from the speeches of Russia, China, and the United States.

require(quanteda.textplots)
## Loading required package: quanteda.textplots
dfm_comparison <- dfm_subset(dfm_un, country %in% c("Russia", "China", "United States"))

set.seed(1234)
textplot_wordcloud(dfm_comparison, max_words = 65, comparison = TRUE)

We can also compare the top features of high income and non-high income countries. Let’s create a document-level dummy variable for income level and then plot a comparison word cloud.

# add income dummy variable to DFM
docvars(dfm_un, "dummy_income") <- factor(ifelse(docvars(dfm_un, "gdp_per_capita") > 12500, "High Income", "Non-High Income"))

# create new dfm based on income groups and plot comparison wordcloud
dfm_income <- dfm_subset(dfm_un, dummy_income %in% c("High Income", "Non-High Income"))
dfm_income <- dfm_group(dfm_income, groups = dummy_income)
textplot_wordcloud(dfm_income, comparison = TRUE, max_words = 200, min_size = 0.2, max_size = 3, fixed_aspect = FALSE)

Keyness

Keyness is a measure that takes into account the extent to which features are specific to a particular document (or group of documents) when compared to the remaining corpus, while accounting for the fact that some features might be too rare. We can, therefore, identify frequent words in documents found in a “target” and “reference” group.

Let’s perform a relative frequency analysis between the speech of the United States (Trump) and that of China (Xi Jinping).

dfm_keyness <- dfm_subset(dfm_un, country %in% c("United States", "China"))
dfm_keyness <- dfm_group(dfm_keyness, groups = country)

# Calculate keyness and set the United States (Donald Trump) as the target group
keyness_stat <- textstat_keyness(dfm_keyness, target = "United States")

# Plot keyness calculations
textplot_keyness(keyness_stat, labelsize = 3)

Readability/Lexical Diversity

We can also approximate how complex a given speech is. One approach is to rely on readability scores. There are a whole range of readability measures available to us and offered by the quanteda library. Let’s use the Flesch-Kincaid measure on the UNGA speeches. Note that we will pass the original corpus to calculate the readability of the speeches. Then we will compare the readability of a select number of countries.

rd <- textstat_readability(un_corpus, measure = "Flesch.Kincaid") # calculate readability scores
rd_subset <- dplyr::filter(rd, document %in% c("United States", "European Union", "Germany", "Ireland", "France", "Sweden"))

#plot readability of subset
ggplot(rd_subset, aes(x = document, y = Flesch.Kincaid)) + 
  geom_bar(stat = "identity", width=0.5) +
  theme_minimal() +
  coord_flip()

It looks like Trump is not as simple as one might think! :) What if we use a simple measure of lexical diversity (TTR)? Note that here we will use the DFM as input.

ld <- textstat_lexdiv(dfm_un, measure = "TTR") # calculate lexical diversity score
ld_subset <- dplyr::filter(ld, document %in% c("United States", "European Union", "Germany", "Ireland", "France", "Sweden"))

#plot lexical diversity of subset
ggplot(ld_subset, aes(x = document, y = TTR)) + 
  geom_bar(stat = "identity", width=0.5) +
  theme_minimal() +
  coord_flip()

However, if we use this measure of complexity, we see that the United States is the most simple of the set of leader speeches.

Text similarity using cosine similarity

We can calculate similarity metrics to determine documents that are similar to eachother based on their feature frequencies. In quanteda we can use textstat_simil to calculate cosine similarity which is a popular such metric.

Note that we will weight the DFM by term frequency-inverse document frequency (tf-idf) instead of just relying on term frequency. The higher the tf-idf weight, the more rare the token. This weighting helps up-weight more predictive tokens.

Let’s determine which leaders’ speeches were closest to that of the United States (2017).

dfm_un_tfidf <- dfm_tfidf(dfm_un)
cosine_sim <- textstat_simil(dfm_un_tfidf, margin="documents", method="cosine")
cosine_sim_list <- as.list(cosine_sim) 


cosine_sim_usa <- cosine_sim_list["United States"]
head(cosine_sim_usa$`United States`, 20) # display top 20 most similar speeches
